b'<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>\n\n\n<!DOCTYPE workbook_page PUBLIC " -//Carnegie Mellon University//DTD Workbook Page MathML 3.8//EN" "http://oli.web.cmu.edu/dtd/oli_workbook_page_mathml_3_8.dtd">\n\n<workbook_page id="p5a_gravimetric" xmlns:cmd="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/content/metadata/2.1/"\n    xmlns:bib="http://bibtexml.sf.net/" xmlns:pref="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/preferences/"\n    xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" xmlns:theme="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/presentation/"\n    xmlns:wb="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/activity/workbook/">\n\n\n    <head>\n        <title>Application of Stoichiometry: Gravimetric Analysis</title>\n        <objref idref="stoich"/>\n    </head>\n\n    <body>\n\n        <p>A gravimetric analysis is a process in which a sample is subjected to some treatment that\n            causes a change in the physical state of the analyte that permits its separation from\n            the other components of the sample. Mass measurements of the sample, the isolated\n            analyte, or some other component of the analysis system, used along with the known\n            stoichiometry of the compounds involved, permit calculation of the analyte\n            concentration. Gravimetric methods were the first techniques used for quantitative\n            chemical analysis, and they remain important tools in the modern chemistry\n            laboratory.</p>\n        <p>The required change of state in a gravimetric analysis may be achieved by various\n            physical and chemical processes. A common gravimetric technique is one in which the\n            analyte is subjected to a precipitation reaction. The precipitate is typically isolated\n            from the reaction mixture by filtration, carefully dried, and then weighed. The mass of\n            the precipitate may then be used, along with relevant stoichiometric relationships, to\n            calculate analyte amount and/or concentration. Watch the video below to see the\n            gravimetric analysis process involving the precipitation of analyte in detail. The\n            example that follows the video shows the calculations for determining the concentration\n            of [Pb<sup>2+</sup>].</p>\n        <youtube src="tk4Tr-CbLbY" height="450" width="800"/>\n        <example>\n            <title>Calculating the Concentration of a Solution with Gravimetric Analysis</title>\n            <p>25.00 mL of the Pb<sup>2+</sup> solution of unknown concentration when treated with\n                excess KI produced 0.1425 g of PbI<sub>2</sub> precipitate, as seen in the video\n                above. What is the [Pb<sup>2+</sup>] in the unknown solution?</p>\n            <p>Calculate the percent of Pb<sup>2+</sup> in PbI<sub>2</sub>.</p>\n            <formula>$$\\frac{207.2\\;\\frac{\\mathrm g}{\\mathrm{mol}}}{461\\;\\frac{\\mathrm g}{\\mathrm{mol}}}\\;\\times\\;100\\;=\\;44.946\\%\\;\\mathrm{Pb}^{2+}\\;\\mathrm{in}\\;{\\mathrm{PbI}}_2$$</formula>\n            <p>Calculate the mass of Pb<sup>2+</sup> in the PbI<sub>2</sub> precipitate.</p>\n            <formula>$$0.44946\\;\\times\\;0.1425\\;\\mathrm g\\;=\\;0.064048\\;\\mathrm\n                g\\;\\mathrm{Pb}^{2+\\;}\\mathrm{in}\\;\\mathrm{precipitate}$$</formula>\n            <p>Convert mass of Pb<sup>2+</sup> to moles Pb<sup>2+</sup>.</p>\n            <formula>$$0.064048\\;\\mathrm\n                g\\;\\mathrm{Pb}^{2+\\;}\\times\\;\\frac{1\\;\\mathrm{mol}\\;\\mathrm{Pb}^{2+}}{207.2\\;\\mathrm\n                g\\;\\mathrm{Pb}^{2+}}\\;=\\;3.0911\\times10^{-4}\\;\\mathrm{mol}\\;\\mathrm{Pb}^{2+}$$</formula>\n            <p>Given the moles of Pb<sup>2+</sup> present in 25.00 mL of solution, calculate the\n                    [Pb<sup>2+</sup>].</p>\n            <formula>$$\\lbrack\\mathrm{Pb}^{2+}\\rbrack\\;=\\;\\frac{3.0911\\times10^{-4}\\;\\mathrm{mol}}{0.02500\\;\\mathrm\n                L}\\;=\\;0.01236\\;\\mathrm M$$</formula>\n        </example>\n        <example>\n            <title>Calculating Percent of Component in Mixture with Gravimetric Analysis</title>\n            <p>A mixture of salts, MgSO<sub>4</sub> and NaNO<sub>3</sub>, has a mass of 1.4520 g.\n                The solid mixture is dissolved in water and treated with an excess of\n                    Ba(NO<sub>3</sub>)<sub>2</sub>, resulting in the precipitation of 0.6168 g of\n                    BaSO<sub>4</sub>.</p>\n            <formula>$${\\mathrm{MgSO}}_4(aq)\\;+\\;\\mathrm{Ba}({\\mathrm{NO}}_3)_2(aq)\\;\\;\\longrightarrow\\;\\;{\\mathrm{BaSO}}_4(s)\\;+\\;\\mathrm{Mg}({\\mathrm{NO}}_3)_2(aq)$$</formula>\n            <p>What is the mass percent of MgSO<sub>4</sub> in the mixture?</p>\n            <p>Calculate the mass of MgSO<sub>4</sub> that would yield the provided precipitate\n                mass. </p>\n            <formula>$$\\require{cancel}0.6168\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm\n                g\\;{\\mathrm{BaSO}}_4}\\times\\frac{1\\cancel{\\;\\mathrm{mol}\\;{\\mathrm{BaSO}}_4}}{233.43\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm\n                g\\;{\\mathrm{BaSO}}_4}}\\;\\times\\;\\frac{1\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm{mol}\\;{\\mathrm{MgSO}}_4}}{1\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm{mol}\\;{\\mathrm{BaSO}}_4}}\\;\\times\\;\\frac{120.37\\;\\mathrm\n                g\\;{\\mathrm{MgSO}}_4}{1\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm{mol}\\;{\\mathrm{MgSO}}_4}}\\;=\\;0.3181\\;\\mathrm\n                g\\;{\\mathrm{MgSO}}_4$$</formula>\n            <p>Calculate the mass percent of MgSO<sub>4</sub> in the sample mixture.</p>\n            <formula>$$\\begin{array}{l}\\mathrm{percent}\\;{\\mathrm{MgSO}}_4\\;=\\;\\frac{\\mathrm{mass}\\;{\\mathrm{MgSO}}_4}{\\;\\mathrm{mass}\\;\\mathrm{sample}}\\;\\times\\;100\\%\\\\\\\\\\frac{\\;0.3181\\;\\mathrm\n                g}{\\;1.4520\\;\\mathrm g}\\;\\times\\;100\\%\\;=\\;21.91\\%\\end{array}$$</formula>\n         \n\n        </example>\n        <wb:inline idref="gravimetric_lbd" purpose="learnbydoing"/>\n\n    </body>\n</workbook_page>\n'